WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.930 --> 00:00:06.600
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:08.330 --> 00:00:10.480
LAMA TSOMO: Well, I'm
excited to be here.

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:12.100
Google's pretty famous.

00:00:12.100 --> 00:00:16.170
And I never expected to
even end up here at all.

00:00:16.170 --> 00:00:20.580
And to be able to share my
favorite things with you guys

00:00:20.580 --> 00:00:24.040
is just such an
honor and pleasure.

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:27.540
And, of course, I've shared
the benefits of Google,

00:00:27.540 --> 00:00:31.180
as has just about everybody
all across the planet,

00:00:31.180 --> 00:00:36.649
so kind of a nice cycle
that I get to partake in.

00:00:36.649 --> 00:00:38.940
Hopefully there will be some
benefit both from the book

00:00:38.940 --> 00:00:41.810
and from the talk today.

00:00:41.810 --> 00:00:44.700
So everybody has
come from busy lives,

00:00:44.700 --> 00:00:48.980
whether you're viewing
the video or actually

00:00:48.980 --> 00:00:51.780
sitting in person
right now, and so I'd

00:00:51.780 --> 00:00:58.390
like for everybody to just stop
and take a moment to be quiet.

00:00:58.390 --> 00:01:00.449
We so rarely do it
even for a moment.

00:01:11.620 --> 00:01:16.620
So while you're
sitting here you might

00:01:16.620 --> 00:01:18.217
think you're doing nothing.

00:01:21.140 --> 00:01:25.580
I would say there are a
couple of things you're doing.

00:01:25.580 --> 00:01:31.310
One thing is, you're
paying attention, perhaps

00:01:31.310 --> 00:01:32.195
to this lady talking.

00:01:35.730 --> 00:01:38.810
And there's something
else you're doing,

00:01:38.810 --> 00:01:42.750
and you do it all the time.

00:01:42.750 --> 00:01:44.618
You hardly ever notice
you're doing it.

00:01:47.900 --> 00:01:49.690
You even do it when
you're sleeping.

00:01:53.840 --> 00:01:57.056
So as you might have
guessed, you're breathing.

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:03.570
But we're so busy with all
kinds of other things we're

00:02:03.570 --> 00:02:07.290
paying attention to out there
that we don't pay attention

00:02:07.290 --> 00:02:09.970
to something so
simple and present

00:02:09.970 --> 00:02:14.440
as the breathing
going on in here.

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:16.670
So I ask you just
to take a moment

00:02:16.670 --> 00:02:20.460
and pay attention to this
breathing that you're doing.

00:02:24.680 --> 00:02:31.690
And not saying, I am breathing,
but just the experience

00:02:31.690 --> 00:02:34.336
of the belly moving as it moves.

00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:47.770
Or maybe you pay
attention and notice

00:02:47.770 --> 00:02:53.040
the coolness in your nostrils
and mouth as the air moves.

00:03:04.140 --> 00:03:05.480
Congratulations.

00:03:05.480 --> 00:03:08.270
You were just meditating.

00:03:08.270 --> 00:03:14.470
[CHUCKLES] It doesn't have to
be some big, mystical thing.

00:03:14.470 --> 00:03:19.130
For a long time, early on
in my efforts to meditate,

00:03:19.130 --> 00:03:22.910
I had all these ideas about what
meditation was supposed to be.

00:03:22.910 --> 00:03:28.780
So I thought it was maybe
some kind of hypnotic state,

00:03:28.780 --> 00:03:32.260
or I thought I was
supposed to stop my brain.

00:03:32.260 --> 00:03:34.660
And the brain is a
thinking machine.

00:03:34.660 --> 00:03:36.710
It manages, it handles thoughts.

00:03:36.710 --> 00:03:41.290
And it turns out, those things
were totally inaccurate.

00:03:41.290 --> 00:03:43.800
But I didn't get a chance to
have meditation instruction

00:03:43.800 --> 00:03:47.870
for a long time, so
I kept sort of having

00:03:47.870 --> 00:03:49.940
these many misconceptions
and thinking,

00:03:49.940 --> 00:03:51.360
I'm a terrible meditator.

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:54.660
Which, by the way, saying
that mantra to yourself

00:03:54.660 --> 00:03:56.660
is not conducive to meditation.

00:03:56.660 --> 00:03:58.420
I've proven this.

00:03:58.420 --> 00:04:03.420
I've proven a lot of ways
not to meditate, by the way.

00:04:03.420 --> 00:04:08.640
So another thing
I proved was what

00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:11.620
happens when I don't meditate.

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:15.240
Though because I finally got so
discouraged, because I thought,

00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:16.740
I'm just not meditating well.

00:04:16.740 --> 00:04:18.350
I'm not cut out for this.

00:04:18.350 --> 00:04:20.040
My mind wanders
all over the place,

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:23.030
I generate lots of thoughts,
I'm just a terrible meditator.

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:24.030
I'm wasting my time.

00:04:24.030 --> 00:04:25.140
Forget it.

00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:29.740
So I stopped even trying
to do daily meditation.

00:04:29.740 --> 00:04:33.430
And I didn't notice
it right away,

00:04:33.430 --> 00:04:39.450
but actually my life started
to get more and more off-track.

00:04:39.450 --> 00:04:42.660
And after five years of
doing my personal experiment

00:04:42.660 --> 00:04:46.070
in not meditating,
I found myself

00:04:46.070 --> 00:04:49.290
really off-track in my
life, not doing the things

00:04:49.290 --> 00:04:53.400
that really meant something to
me and that were right for me

00:04:53.400 --> 00:04:55.350
in my life.

00:04:55.350 --> 00:05:00.180
And it happened by little,
tiny decision after decision.

00:05:00.180 --> 00:05:03.340
And we make thousands of
those every day, actually.

00:05:03.340 --> 00:05:08.180
And they go by in a flash
and we don't even realize it.

00:05:08.180 --> 00:05:12.540
So not coming to
myself every day

00:05:12.540 --> 00:05:16.810
and always having the lens
turned outward, never turning

00:05:16.810 --> 00:05:19.480
it inward and just kind of
taking a break on responding

00:05:19.480 --> 00:05:23.420
to outside things, it turned
out that, even though I

00:05:23.420 --> 00:05:28.360
was doing a bad job of it
with just sitting with myself

00:05:28.360 --> 00:05:35.010
and just being
quiet, I wasn't there

00:05:35.010 --> 00:05:40.920
then when that little
knowing would bubble up.

00:05:40.920 --> 00:05:43.694
So what I always think of
is like the eight ball.

00:05:43.694 --> 00:05:45.360
You know that thing
where you turn it up

00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:47.330
and this little
thing bubbles up?

00:05:47.330 --> 00:05:50.450
So, I wasn't there to see it.

00:05:50.450 --> 00:05:55.050
But my deepest self, my true
self knew what was right

00:05:55.050 --> 00:05:58.060
for me, what was on track
for me, and what wasn't.

00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:01.190
And I just wasn't
there to hear it.

00:06:01.190 --> 00:06:05.680
So I kind of woke up
to things five years

00:06:05.680 --> 00:06:07.660
after not meditating,
you know, beginning

00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:13.330
my non-meditation
program, and I realized

00:06:13.330 --> 00:06:15.690
I was living in the
place that wasn't right

00:06:15.690 --> 00:06:19.360
for me, with people that
were not right for me,

00:06:19.360 --> 00:06:22.850
doing stuff that wasn't
right for me, on and on.

00:06:22.850 --> 00:06:28.080
And somehow I guess my inner
self just kind of broke

00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:32.300
through the distraction
and I was able to hear it.

00:06:32.300 --> 00:06:36.790
So I thought, oh my gosh,
even my pathetic attempts

00:06:36.790 --> 00:06:41.130
at meditation at least I
was there to hear more.

00:06:41.130 --> 00:06:44.530
So I want to meditate every day.

00:06:44.530 --> 00:06:47.660
And you know, just kind
of through those thousands

00:06:47.660 --> 00:06:50.130
of little decisions,
a little more track.

00:06:50.130 --> 00:06:51.970
Hopefully more
and more on track.

00:06:51.970 --> 00:06:55.120
But this time I want
to get instruction.

00:06:55.120 --> 00:06:57.600
So as a kid I played piano.

00:06:57.600 --> 00:07:00.370
And I got much better
at piano for having

00:07:00.370 --> 00:07:01.420
gone to a piano teacher.

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:03.930
It turns out, it really helps
to go to a piano teacher,

00:07:03.930 --> 00:07:05.450
and practice.

00:07:05.450 --> 00:07:09.670
So I thought, maybe the same
principle works for meditation.

00:07:09.670 --> 00:07:16.800
So I set about trying to find
a teacher who was right for me,

00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:20.580
and I made a list of
the qualities I wanted.

00:07:20.580 --> 00:07:23.560
They had to be really
highly-realized,

00:07:23.560 --> 00:07:25.220
highly-accomplished
meditator, really

00:07:25.220 --> 00:07:28.420
knowledgeable in their
tradition and so on.

00:07:28.420 --> 00:07:31.960
And one thing I forgot
to put on the list was,

00:07:31.960 --> 00:07:33.770
must speak English.

00:07:33.770 --> 00:07:36.240
So he still doesn't
speak English.

00:07:36.240 --> 00:07:39.110
He's a Tibetan Lama.

00:07:39.110 --> 00:07:41.770
And so I ended up having
to learn Tibetan just

00:07:41.770 --> 00:07:44.828
to be able to converse with him.

00:07:44.828 --> 00:07:47.470
And it's a very difficult
language to learn.

00:07:47.470 --> 00:07:51.160
But it turns out, the same
principles are at work.

00:07:51.160 --> 00:07:53.030
You can do it a few
minutes every day,

00:07:53.030 --> 00:07:55.230
but it has to be every day.

00:07:55.230 --> 00:08:00.090
And sometimes having total
immersion is very important.

00:08:00.090 --> 00:08:03.890
And that turns out also to
be true with meditation.

00:08:03.890 --> 00:08:06.930
And total immersion in
the Buddhist tradition

00:08:06.930 --> 00:08:09.680
is called retreat.

00:08:09.680 --> 00:08:14.180
So I did both daily
meditation and retreats

00:08:14.180 --> 00:08:15.570
and studied with this Lama.

00:08:15.570 --> 00:08:18.010
And he really took me on.

00:08:18.010 --> 00:08:22.770
And I would try one practice
and it was so beneficial,

00:08:22.770 --> 00:08:25.670
I was feeling so much
better and able to handle

00:08:25.670 --> 00:08:31.160
the challenges of life better,
and even in the moment of life

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:34.169
for having been consistently
meditating and doing

00:08:34.169 --> 00:08:37.309
these retreats, I got more
and more excited about it

00:08:37.309 --> 00:08:39.559
and I wanted to do the next
practice and the next one.

00:08:39.559 --> 00:08:42.400
And one thing led to another
and, as my kids put it,

00:08:42.400 --> 00:08:45.010
I was lama-nated.

00:08:45.010 --> 00:08:47.430
So I am now a Lama myself.

00:08:47.430 --> 00:08:49.410
But not on the
level of my teacher.

00:08:49.410 --> 00:08:51.880
I still take from him.

00:08:51.880 --> 00:08:55.140
But I have certainly
learned a lot.

00:08:55.140 --> 00:08:59.140
And I've had a chance to teach
a lot and work with Westerners,

00:08:59.140 --> 00:09:01.770
and that's been really
rewarding work for me.

00:09:01.770 --> 00:09:08.570
So I've been more and
more on track for me.

00:09:08.570 --> 00:09:13.090
And so what you've
probably heard a lot about

00:09:13.090 --> 00:09:16.190
is the benefits of
meditation for longevity,

00:09:16.190 --> 00:09:19.270
the immune system,
working better.

00:09:19.270 --> 00:09:22.770
You can even multitask
better because it turns out

00:09:22.770 --> 00:09:25.590
that your brain is actually--
your conscious mind is only

00:09:25.590 --> 00:09:27.630
paying attention to
one thing at a time,

00:09:27.630 --> 00:09:29.640
but it's shuttling very quickly.

00:09:29.640 --> 00:09:31.990
And it appears to us
that we're multitasking,

00:09:31.990 --> 00:09:34.450
but actually were shuttling.

00:09:34.450 --> 00:09:37.780
And meditation--
in fact, the one

00:09:37.780 --> 00:09:41.090
that I'm going to
be teaching you more

00:09:41.090 --> 00:09:44.210
formally in a little
bit, and you already

00:09:44.210 --> 00:09:48.750
started to do-- that
helps with multitasking.

00:09:48.750 --> 00:09:51.560
So there are all kinds of
wonderful studies coming out.

00:09:51.560 --> 00:09:56.090
Pain-- helping a great
deal with pain, compassion,

00:09:56.090 --> 00:09:58.600
all kinds of benefits.

00:09:58.600 --> 00:10:01.840
What I wanted to talk about
and focus more on today

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:06.070
was living in meaningful life.

00:10:06.070 --> 00:10:10.020
And they've only just started
doing a lot of studies on that.

00:10:10.020 --> 00:10:13.710
There's one 50-year
study that was

00:10:13.710 --> 00:10:19.240
done in a book called "Why Good
Things Happen to Good People."

00:10:19.240 --> 00:10:23.820
And that's a very
interesting study.

00:10:23.820 --> 00:10:26.700
But what I really
want to focus on

00:10:26.700 --> 00:10:31.400
is more my understanding
from the Buddhist side of it,

00:10:31.400 --> 00:10:35.880
why is it that we all want
to live a meaningful life?

00:10:35.880 --> 00:10:39.060
And why is it that so often
a meaningful life involves

00:10:39.060 --> 00:10:41.300
somehow benefiting others?

00:10:44.540 --> 00:10:46.040
We can just take a
little vote here.

00:10:46.040 --> 00:10:51.640
How many people here feel
that a meaningful life to them

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:56.202
would be somehow, in some
way benefiting others?

00:10:58.900 --> 00:10:59.400
OK.

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:00.590
It's unanimous.

00:11:00.590 --> 00:11:04.470
We have passed by a
unanimous measure.

00:11:04.470 --> 00:11:08.140
This is what I always
find to be the case.

00:11:08.140 --> 00:11:10.250
Why is that?

00:11:10.250 --> 00:11:12.120
Why wouldn't it
be something else?

00:11:12.120 --> 00:11:14.480
And even in the
studies on the brain,

00:11:14.480 --> 00:11:17.337
what makes us happier for
longer is helping somebody else.

00:11:20.180 --> 00:11:22.930
So I'll give you a
Buddhist metaphor.

00:11:27.110 --> 00:11:30.630
Let's say that we are
all from one source,

00:11:30.630 --> 00:11:34.200
that everything is
created from one source.

00:11:34.200 --> 00:11:37.470
And the physicist
David Bohm would

00:11:37.470 --> 00:11:40.970
agree with this, that if you
sort of break it all down

00:11:40.970 --> 00:11:44.170
and you went into subatomic
physics-- in the early days

00:11:44.170 --> 00:11:48.030
it was subatomic physics--
and if we get down

00:11:48.030 --> 00:11:50.020
to that level, then
the inside of my skin

00:11:50.020 --> 00:11:54.230
and the outside of my skin--
it doesn't look any different.

00:11:54.230 --> 00:11:58.010
So we can kind of get down
to a common denominator.

00:11:58.010 --> 00:12:02.490
So if that root is a
common denominator,

00:12:02.490 --> 00:12:06.180
let's use the
metaphor of an ocean.

00:12:06.180 --> 00:12:08.560
So there's one great
big, vast ocean,

00:12:08.560 --> 00:12:12.600
and it makes all these different
waves, and each wave is unique.

00:12:12.600 --> 00:12:15.040
There are no two that
are exactly alike,

00:12:15.040 --> 00:12:16.930
and you can't freeze a wave.

00:12:16.930 --> 00:12:19.750
They just keep
changing and moving,

00:12:19.750 --> 00:12:23.977
and their shape
changes and so on.

00:12:23.977 --> 00:12:25.810
But the important thing
that I'm focusing on

00:12:25.810 --> 00:12:28.392
is the uniqueness of all
the waves and the fact

00:12:28.392 --> 00:12:29.850
that they're actually
all connected

00:12:29.850 --> 00:12:32.200
and part of this one big ocean.

00:12:32.200 --> 00:12:39.420
So each of us is a wave,
and yet we're all connected.

00:12:39.420 --> 00:12:43.880
So why else would
it be that when

00:12:43.880 --> 00:12:50.200
we see a suffering stray
puppy, our heart is moved

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:54.040
and we suffer with
them a little bit?

00:12:54.040 --> 00:12:55.870
Now, most of the time
we're too distracted,

00:12:55.870 --> 00:13:00.360
but I believe that somebody
who is really accomplished,

00:13:00.360 --> 00:13:03.020
somebody like His
Holiness the Dalai Lama--

00:13:03.020 --> 00:13:07.700
the cover boy for
my book-- he can

00:13:07.700 --> 00:13:11.520
feel a huge amount of suffering
on a much more vast level,

00:13:11.520 --> 00:13:14.990
and really suffers with.

00:13:14.990 --> 00:13:19.550
So naturally then we're inspired
to do something about that.

00:13:19.550 --> 00:13:21.400
And I've noticed that,
for example, people

00:13:21.400 --> 00:13:23.740
who have survived
rape really want

00:13:23.740 --> 00:13:27.960
to work in the field of helping
others who have survived rape.

00:13:27.960 --> 00:13:31.730
Or I was listening
recently to somebody

00:13:31.730 --> 00:13:34.350
whose son was killed
by gang violence

00:13:34.350 --> 00:13:39.360
and he had to go on this
deep journey of forgiveness,

00:13:39.360 --> 00:13:42.480
got to know the family
of the killer of his son,

00:13:42.480 --> 00:13:44.930
got to know the
killer of his son,

00:13:44.930 --> 00:13:48.130
and became good friends
with the grandfather

00:13:48.130 --> 00:13:52.000
of the one who killed his son.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.960
And now the families
have become very close.

00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:58.490
And he does presentations
along with the grandfather.

00:13:58.490 --> 00:14:00.550
You work with gang
members and work

00:14:00.550 --> 00:14:05.570
with families who've lost people
from gang violence and so on,

00:14:05.570 --> 00:14:08.830
and he said he's leading
the most satisfying life he

00:14:08.830 --> 00:14:10.590
could possibly imagine.

00:14:10.590 --> 00:14:15.290
Of course he misses his son, but
this is a way that he could--

00:14:15.290 --> 00:14:19.150
it set him on what I
call a redemption story.

00:14:19.150 --> 00:14:22.930
And I think we all have
something like that.

00:14:22.930 --> 00:14:25.900
And somehow we've-- I know
somebody else who spent seven

00:14:25.900 --> 00:14:28.130
years in a very poor
place-- I'm sorry,

00:14:28.130 --> 00:14:32.220
a year in a very poor
place when she was seven,

00:14:32.220 --> 00:14:38.450
and she was so moved and felt
such pain that she had a roof

00:14:38.450 --> 00:14:41.820
over her head and food to eat
and they didn't, it set her

00:14:41.820 --> 00:14:46.420
on a path of helping
bring benefit to everyone.

00:14:46.420 --> 00:14:50.020
And she's still following
that today in her 50s.

00:14:50.020 --> 00:14:56.620
So how do we pursue a
life that's meaningful?

00:14:56.620 --> 00:14:58.440
We want our lives to
count for something.

00:14:58.440 --> 00:15:02.290
And whatever our unique
gifts are as this wave,

00:15:02.290 --> 00:15:08.540
we want to bring that to all of
the ocean and benefit somehow.

00:15:08.540 --> 00:15:09.770
How do we find that?

00:15:09.770 --> 00:15:13.470
How do we stay on
track day to day?

00:15:13.470 --> 00:15:15.680
This is where meditation
can be so helpful.

00:15:15.680 --> 00:15:19.360
And this is really what
I'm more focusing on,

00:15:19.360 --> 00:15:21.280
rather than all of the
other wonderful things

00:15:21.280 --> 00:15:24.620
you've probably read
about in studies.

00:15:24.620 --> 00:15:25.800
So how does that work?

00:15:28.330 --> 00:15:30.130
A couple of things.

00:15:30.130 --> 00:15:33.510
There are many things
I could point to,

00:15:33.510 --> 00:15:35.470
but we don't have a lot of time.

00:15:35.470 --> 00:15:41.720
So one thing I can point
to is, when you sit quietly

00:15:41.720 --> 00:15:44.610
and you're not responding
to the stuff on the outside,

00:15:44.610 --> 00:15:48.270
you're taking a break,
and even the stuff

00:15:48.270 --> 00:15:53.220
that you normally have to think
about and plan about regarding

00:15:53.220 --> 00:15:57.270
your work-- and I think that's
true for a lot of people here.

00:15:57.270 --> 00:16:01.370
You know, it's mental work
that you're doing a lot--

00:16:01.370 --> 00:16:03.960
to take a break from that.

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:06.070
First of all, I have
a lot of mental work.

00:16:06.070 --> 00:16:10.820
Writing books, teaching,
that kind of thing,

00:16:10.820 --> 00:16:14.260
working with our
retreat facility

00:16:14.260 --> 00:16:16.310
that we're building and so on.

00:16:16.310 --> 00:16:17.949
But taking a break
from it and saying,

00:16:17.949 --> 00:16:19.740
I don't have to think
about that right now.

00:16:19.740 --> 00:16:24.290
I have a few minutes where I'm
going to take a real vacation.

00:16:24.290 --> 00:16:26.910
So you can take
a daily vacation.

00:16:26.910 --> 00:16:28.970
Every day, but a real one.

00:16:28.970 --> 00:16:30.940
Not spending a bunch of
money to go to a beach

00:16:30.940 --> 00:16:34.830
or have drinks with
parasols or whatever

00:16:34.830 --> 00:16:40.140
and then still your mind is
churning, but a real vacation.

00:16:40.140 --> 00:16:43.400
And when you do
that it's like you

00:16:43.400 --> 00:16:46.970
get to look into a pond that
normally is all stirred up,

00:16:46.970 --> 00:16:49.000
and there's silt all
through the water

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:50.770
and the waves are
churning around,

00:16:50.770 --> 00:16:53.080
and you let that all settle.

00:16:53.080 --> 00:16:54.930
And the silt settles.

00:16:54.930 --> 00:16:57.240
And the waves
settle a little bit.

00:16:57.240 --> 00:17:01.040
It doesn't have to be
perfect, but we can see more

00:17:01.040 --> 00:17:05.280
what the water really is and
what it looks like all the way

00:17:05.280 --> 00:17:07.349
to the bottom.

00:17:07.349 --> 00:17:08.880
That's what we can
do for ourselves

00:17:08.880 --> 00:17:11.170
in just a few minutes a day.

00:17:11.170 --> 00:17:12.790
The key is to do it every day.

00:17:12.790 --> 00:17:16.800
I learned this with
practicing piano,

00:17:16.800 --> 00:17:18.780
and I learned it with
learning Tibetan.

00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:23.010
it's about doing it every day,
even if only for a few minutes.

00:17:23.010 --> 00:17:26.410
And you will make progress.

00:17:26.410 --> 00:17:31.940
There's a handout that shows the
different stages the brain goes

00:17:31.940 --> 00:17:36.000
through in the process of
forgetting and remembering,

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.180
because what you find you
do over and over again

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:41.780
in meditation-- I'm going to
make this prediction right

00:17:41.780 --> 00:17:45.440
now with confidence-- you're
going to come to this moment

00:17:45.440 --> 00:17:49.140
where you go, oh yeah,
I was meditating.

00:17:49.140 --> 00:17:50.710
Because what you
were doing instead

00:17:50.710 --> 00:17:53.220
was spinning a
movie in your mind.

00:17:53.220 --> 00:17:54.820
So thoughts come and go.

00:17:54.820 --> 00:17:57.640
And we can just sit and let
the thoughts come and go

00:17:57.640 --> 00:18:00.380
as we focus on an
object of support,

00:18:00.380 --> 00:18:03.730
like focusing on the breath.

00:18:03.730 --> 00:18:06.770
But there's going to
come a moment where

00:18:06.770 --> 00:18:09.510
we forget to do that and we
start following after a thought

00:18:09.510 --> 00:18:12.590
and making a story, which
is what we-- we all tend

00:18:12.590 --> 00:18:14.980
to do that, as human beings.

00:18:14.980 --> 00:18:18.070
And it's the making a story
and making this whole movie

00:18:18.070 --> 00:18:24.170
and this continuum that is
now no longer meditation.

00:18:24.170 --> 00:18:28.177
Just having the thought come
and go while you stay present

00:18:28.177 --> 00:18:29.760
and you've just
watched it come and go

00:18:29.760 --> 00:18:32.450
and you didn't go after it,
you're still meditating.

00:18:32.450 --> 00:18:35.790
That's eligible for meditation.

00:18:35.790 --> 00:18:37.920
But as soon as you've
followed after the movie

00:18:37.920 --> 00:18:41.470
and then you say, oh,
yeah, I was meditating.

00:18:41.470 --> 00:18:44.580
So particular parts
of the brain light up

00:18:44.580 --> 00:18:49.040
and it's in the handout
which you're welcome to.

00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:53.580
And so these are desirable
parts of the brain that normally

00:18:53.580 --> 00:18:54.680
don't light up so much.

00:18:54.680 --> 00:18:56.430
We follow after a lot
of thought and make

00:18:56.430 --> 00:18:58.050
a lot of movies all day.

00:18:58.050 --> 00:19:00.350
So that's already a good thing.

00:19:00.350 --> 00:19:01.740
But there's a couple more.

00:19:01.740 --> 00:19:04.960
So after we've remembered,
oh yeah, I was meditating,

00:19:04.960 --> 00:19:08.490
we bring our mind back to
the object of meditation,

00:19:08.490 --> 00:19:12.160
other parts of the brain
light up, also very good.

00:19:12.160 --> 00:19:17.190
And then we attempt to keep our
mind there as long as we can.

00:19:17.190 --> 00:19:22.190
That lights up yet other
desirable parts of the brain.

00:19:22.190 --> 00:19:24.270
And then we forget
again and so it goes.

00:19:24.270 --> 00:19:29.660
So that's a wonderful cycle
that Dan Harris calls--

00:19:29.660 --> 00:19:30.902
you know, the news anchor.

00:19:30.902 --> 00:19:32.610
I don't know if you're
familiar with him.

00:19:32.610 --> 00:19:35.440
He wrote a book on his
stumbling into meditation.

00:19:35.440 --> 00:19:37.580
It's called "10% Happier."

00:19:37.580 --> 00:19:42.310
He refers to this cycle as
bicep curls for the brain.

00:19:42.310 --> 00:19:45.060
So it's just fine to
forget and remember,

00:19:45.060 --> 00:19:46.690
because then you
get to do all that

00:19:46.690 --> 00:19:53.115
and rest freshly in this
peaceful, abiding meditation

00:19:53.115 --> 00:19:53.780
called Samatha.

00:19:58.030 --> 00:20:01.360
So what is my
offering to the world?

00:20:01.360 --> 00:20:03.390
I just want to share that
a little bit with you.

00:20:06.150 --> 00:20:08.830
In my adventure not
meditating and then

00:20:08.830 --> 00:20:12.460
meditating and discovering it
was so much better when I did,

00:20:12.460 --> 00:20:18.340
and I felt so much happier just
ongoing, and so much better

00:20:18.340 --> 00:20:20.927
able to handle
challenges in life.

00:20:20.927 --> 00:20:23.010
I thought, well, I want
to share this with others,

00:20:23.010 --> 00:20:26.940
and I don't want them to have to
wait until they're middle-aged,

00:20:26.940 --> 00:20:29.940
they stumble upon a Lama,
they learn to Tibetan,

00:20:29.940 --> 00:20:34.650
they sit in retreat in Nepal
and on a mountain in Montana,

00:20:34.650 --> 00:20:36.480
you know, for years at a time.

00:20:36.480 --> 00:20:41.400
Cumulatively I've spent
years in meditation retreat.

00:20:41.400 --> 00:20:43.980
I want to make it easy for
Westerners to get started

00:20:43.980 --> 00:20:49.300
and to pursue a path where
they can deepen as much as they

00:20:49.300 --> 00:20:51.600
want to all the way to the end.

00:20:51.600 --> 00:20:55.040
Or at least just be able
to pursue daily meditation

00:20:55.040 --> 00:20:57.430
and have the support for that.

00:20:57.430 --> 00:21:01.470
So I began offering
a weekly class

00:21:01.470 --> 00:21:06.070
and I noticed that
really I needed

00:21:06.070 --> 00:21:08.910
to give more background where
they could just kind of refer

00:21:08.910 --> 00:21:10.640
to it on their own.

00:21:10.640 --> 00:21:12.875
I thought, I've got
to assign a book.

00:21:12.875 --> 00:21:15.500
And also then they don't have to
keep asking the same questions

00:21:15.500 --> 00:21:18.950
because this is so new, they
can just refer to the book.

00:21:18.950 --> 00:21:21.640
Well, I just looked
and looked and I

00:21:21.640 --> 00:21:23.580
couldn't find the book
I was looking for,

00:21:23.580 --> 00:21:25.910
so I thought, well,
I'll just write it.

00:21:25.910 --> 00:21:30.400
That turned out to
be a big project.

00:21:30.400 --> 00:21:33.340
And it grew and grew and grew.

00:21:33.340 --> 00:21:37.950
And now this book is one
of a series of three,

00:21:37.950 --> 00:21:41.710
and it's already,
you know, pretty big.

00:21:41.710 --> 00:21:44.620
But this is the
introductory one.

00:21:44.620 --> 00:21:47.660
And it's assuming absolutely
no prior knowledge.

00:21:47.660 --> 00:21:49.910
And in the back of the book
there are practiced cards.

00:21:49.910 --> 00:21:52.810
So when you want
to remember, OK,

00:21:52.810 --> 00:21:55.770
how do I-- what's the
step-by-step and just

00:21:55.770 --> 00:21:58.230
a few quick notes,
you can have it right

00:21:58.230 --> 00:22:02.800
there wherever it is that you
normally sit and meditate.

00:22:02.800 --> 00:22:08.447
And I also wanted to have more
support than just the book,

00:22:08.447 --> 00:22:10.780
because once I realized I was
going to put this book out

00:22:10.780 --> 00:22:13.820
in the world and not just have
it in a Montana meditation

00:22:13.820 --> 00:22:19.530
group, I thought, well,
people need their groups.

00:22:19.530 --> 00:22:24.620
People need to sit together and
chew on this stuff together.

00:22:24.620 --> 00:22:26.430
And how does this
affect my life?

00:22:26.430 --> 00:22:28.200
How does my life
affect my meditation?

00:22:28.200 --> 00:22:30.330
How do I put these
things together?

00:22:30.330 --> 00:22:32.720
And for people to be able
to chew on that together--

00:22:32.720 --> 00:22:39.150
I've seen how rich that is
and how deeply people connect

00:22:39.150 --> 00:22:41.670
when they have
something to really sink

00:22:41.670 --> 00:22:43.610
their teeth into like that.

00:22:43.610 --> 00:22:44.970
How often do we do that?

00:22:44.970 --> 00:22:46.610
You know, going
to a bar you don't

00:22:46.610 --> 00:22:50.620
have quite the same
quality of conversation.

00:22:50.620 --> 00:22:56.270
So I just suddenly thought,
what if the crew on "How

00:22:56.270 --> 00:23:01.240
I Met Your Mother" had set aside
a weekly time in somebody's

00:23:01.240 --> 00:23:04.800
living room and just talked
about this stuff and, you know,

00:23:04.800 --> 00:23:08.950
road-tested these methods
and talked about their lives

00:23:08.950 --> 00:23:10.320
together in a meaningful way?

00:23:10.320 --> 00:23:13.160
And I give context pieces,
too, and then people

00:23:13.160 --> 00:23:14.060
could chew on that.

00:23:14.060 --> 00:23:17.240
And so we called these
learning circles.

00:23:17.240 --> 00:23:22.170
And we've just
begun setting things

00:23:22.170 --> 00:23:26.420
up so that you can fairly easily
get started with a learning

00:23:26.420 --> 00:23:27.690
circle.

00:23:27.690 --> 00:23:30.880
So you can download a tool kit.

00:23:30.880 --> 00:23:35.300
And really, all
the way through, we

00:23:35.300 --> 00:23:39.620
see it's terribly important
how the group relates

00:23:39.620 --> 00:23:41.730
to each other,
what are the norms.

00:23:41.730 --> 00:23:44.570
And now I'm getting into
a "New York Times" article

00:23:44.570 --> 00:23:49.240
I read about something
called Aristotle, which

00:23:49.240 --> 00:23:52.490
I think you guys know about.

00:23:52.490 --> 00:23:56.440
And I was excited to see
that because that's something

00:23:56.440 --> 00:23:59.900
I feel strongly about
and I wanted to be sure

00:23:59.900 --> 00:24:07.030
that we covered the meditation
instruction, the background,

00:24:07.030 --> 00:24:09.680
sort of the map-- how
does this all work, what

00:24:09.680 --> 00:24:12.700
is the context, and
so on-- and also

00:24:12.700 --> 00:24:17.050
how can we enact these
things in relationship

00:24:17.050 --> 00:24:21.220
to each other in these
small groups that

00:24:21.220 --> 00:24:26.010
are sort of where the rubber
hits the road and even

00:24:26.010 --> 00:24:27.900
in larger groups?

00:24:27.900 --> 00:24:32.050
So I enlisted the help of
my friend Aaron Stern, who's

00:24:32.050 --> 00:24:38.880
sitting right here, because he's
an expert at that third piece,

00:24:38.880 --> 00:24:41.390
the interrelationships
and how to sort

00:24:41.390 --> 00:24:47.440
of enact Buddhism in
relationship with each other.

00:24:47.440 --> 00:24:50.400
Because he is an expert
at that, has developed

00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:51.910
some wonderful methods.

00:24:51.910 --> 00:24:55.500
So we're bringing in some
modern Western methods

00:24:55.500 --> 00:24:59.440
to add to these time-tested
ones from the East.

00:24:59.440 --> 00:25:01.201
And so it's a very
rich combination

00:25:01.201 --> 00:25:02.201
that we wanted to offer.

00:25:05.460 --> 00:25:12.940
I also am really interested in
mixes of ages working together

00:25:12.940 --> 00:25:18.060
because there's-- if you think
back to what we evolved with,

00:25:18.060 --> 00:25:22.060
we evolved in villages and
everybody was mixed together.

00:25:22.060 --> 00:25:25.050
We weren't separated in classes,
sort of Henry Ford-style

00:25:25.050 --> 00:25:28.580
assembly line learning,
which I think is not natural,

00:25:28.580 --> 00:25:30.280
not a way to go, and
I think that's why

00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:34.050
there's a lot of terrible social
dynamics going on in schools.

00:25:34.050 --> 00:25:39.900
And then that's our learning
ground for social dynamics.

00:25:39.900 --> 00:25:43.200
But there can be a richness
in mixing ages together

00:25:43.200 --> 00:25:47.730
because people in
their young adult years

00:25:47.730 --> 00:25:50.510
have a lot of energy and vision.

00:25:50.510 --> 00:25:54.020
They know what's coming
just over the horizon.

00:25:54.020 --> 00:25:56.070
And there's a power in that.

00:25:56.070 --> 00:25:58.950
There's a particular
power in that.

00:25:58.950 --> 00:26:04.420
Then for old people like me,
we've been around a long time

00:26:04.420 --> 00:26:07.740
and so we've learned
some techniques,

00:26:07.740 --> 00:26:09.750
educated ourselves
in some things,

00:26:09.750 --> 00:26:13.420
and just spent a lot of
time experiencing life.

00:26:13.420 --> 00:26:16.620
And so I think this can be
a very powerful combination.

00:26:16.620 --> 00:26:21.870
But again, we need to know how
to work together, and want to.

00:26:21.870 --> 00:26:24.070
But I think that's what
were designed to do.

00:26:24.070 --> 00:26:27.070
And at this time in
the world we all need

00:26:27.070 --> 00:26:31.200
to get together and bring all
of our superpowers together.

00:26:31.200 --> 00:26:34.220
Our individual
ones as unique ways

00:26:34.220 --> 00:26:37.710
and our different
demographics, all of it

00:26:37.710 --> 00:26:41.750
to come together to solve
the very big challenges

00:26:41.750 --> 00:26:44.515
of this time.

00:26:44.515 --> 00:26:46.660
I think we're ready for
some question and answer,

00:26:46.660 --> 00:26:51.490
and then I will more formally
teach you Samatha practice

00:26:51.490 --> 00:26:52.741
to finish up the session.

00:26:52.741 --> 00:26:54.240
FEMALE SPEAKER:
Thank you very much.

00:26:54.240 --> 00:26:55.730
I have so many questions.

00:26:55.730 --> 00:26:57.297
I was writing ferociously.

00:26:57.297 --> 00:26:59.005
LAMA TSOMO: Your page
is full of writing.

00:26:59.005 --> 00:26:59.963
FEMALE SPEAKER: I know.

00:26:59.963 --> 00:27:02.450
It's really cathartic
to write by hand

00:27:02.450 --> 00:27:04.320
and not be typing for once.

00:27:04.320 --> 00:27:07.210
I need to take a few
notes back to my desk.

00:27:07.210 --> 00:27:10.880
So you just touched on this
at the-- sort of the end

00:27:10.880 --> 00:27:13.300
with project Aristotle.

00:27:13.300 --> 00:27:15.420
And I think we're
fortunate enough

00:27:15.420 --> 00:27:18.900
to work at a place that
supports developing

00:27:18.900 --> 00:27:21.490
a practice of mindfulness
through things like gPause

00:27:21.490 --> 00:27:24.460
and Search Inside Yourself and
having beautiful meditation

00:27:24.460 --> 00:27:26.110
rooms.

00:27:26.110 --> 00:27:29.710
But it still is very much
an individual process.

00:27:29.710 --> 00:27:32.050
It's very much an
individual journey,

00:27:32.050 --> 00:27:34.350
unless you're lucky
enough to find a teacher.

00:27:34.350 --> 00:27:38.350
And the general rule of thumb
at Google is, is don't be evil

00:27:38.350 --> 00:27:39.170
or don't be a jerk.

00:27:39.170 --> 00:27:39.440
You know?

00:27:39.440 --> 00:27:41.023
Nobody wants to work
with that person.

00:27:41.023 --> 00:27:43.410
But I'm wondering
what your thoughts

00:27:43.410 --> 00:27:48.090
are on bridging the gap between
sort of this individual, really

00:27:48.090 --> 00:27:51.030
difficult, deep-rooted
practice and then bringing it

00:27:51.030 --> 00:27:54.730
to the workplace and
not necessarily taking

00:27:54.730 --> 00:27:57.310
your whole team to the
meditation room to meditate,

00:27:57.310 --> 00:28:02.110
but how can we benefit and
how can our teams benefit

00:28:02.110 --> 00:28:04.420
from the work that we're
doing individually?

00:28:04.420 --> 00:28:06.010
LAMA TSOMO: Mm-hm.

00:28:06.010 --> 00:28:10.780
So at Namchak we do have a
meditation room also, and at

00:28:10.780 --> 00:28:15.780
lunchtime people-- whoever
